        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1941-08-20T10:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1941-08-20T10:00:00-05:00" n="69"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d69">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.0011 European War 1939/14163: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in the Soviet Union</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Steinhardt</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Moscow</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1941-08-20T18:00:00+03:00"
                            >August 20, 1941—6 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received 6:25 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1544. The Swedish Minister told me this afternoon that when Günther was in
                    Helsinki on May 6, he received definite and positive assurances from Ryti,
                    Witting and Walden that in the event of a German attack on the Soviet Union,
                    Finland would remain neutral and “defend its neutrality against Germany if
                    necessary”, and that the Finnish Government had given no notice to the Swedish
                    Government <pb facs="0070" n="58" xml:id="pg_58"/> of its intended entry into
                    the war against Soviet Union on the side of Germany. He said that the limited
                    amount of food moving from Sweden to Finland since the outbreak of the
                    Soviet-German war was being sent in response to German pressure.</p>
                <p>Assarsson attributed the Finnish entry into the war to pressure on the Government
                    from high Finnish military circles.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Steinhardt</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
